  "local_port": 42844,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I design in sketch?",
  "response": "Designing in **Sketch** involves creating vector-based designs, wireframes, prototypes, and more for apps, websites, and other digital projects. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you get started:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Understand the Basics**\n- **Workspace**: Sketch\u2019s interface includes a toolbar (left), canvas (center), inspector (right), and layers list (left).\n- **Artboards**: Artboards are the frames where you create your designs. Use them to define screen sizes or design sections.\n- **Vector Shapes**: Sketch is vector-based, meaning all elements are scalable without losing quality.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Set Up Your Project**\n1. **Choose an Artboard Size**:\n   - Start by selecting an artboard template (e.g., iPhone, Desktop, Custom) from the **Insert > Artboard** menu.\n   - Customize the size in the Inspector panel if needed.\n2. **Grids and Layouts**:\n   - Enable grids (**View > Canvas > Grid Settings**) to align elements.\n   - Use layout settings (**Layout Settings**) for responsive design (e.g., column grids).\n\n---\n\n### **3. Add Elements**\n- **Shapes**: Use the **Insert > Shape** menu to add rectangles, circles, lines, etc.\n- **Text**: Add text with the **Text Tool (T)**. Customize fonts, sizes, and colors in the Inspector.\n- **Images**: Drag and drop images or use **Insert > Image**.\n- **Symbols**: Create reusable components (e.g., buttons, icons) with **Create Symbol**. Edit once, and updates apply everywhere.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Style and Customize**\n- **Colors**: Use the color picker in the Inspector to apply fills, borders, and gradients.\n- **Shadows and Blurs**: Add depth with layer styles like shadows, blurs, and fills.\n- **Typography**: Adjust font styles, spacing, and alignment for text elements.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Organize Your Design**\n- **Layers**: Use the layers list to group, rename, and organize elements.\n- **Groups**: Select multiple layers and group them (**Cmd + G**) for easier management.\n- **Naming**: Name layers and groups descriptively for clarity.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Use Plugins**\nSketch has a rich plugin ecosystem to enhance your workflow:\n- **Content Generator**: Fill designs with placeholder text and images.\n- **Sketch Runner**: Quickly search and execute commands.\n- **Anima**: Create responsive and animated prototypes.\n- Download plugins from **Sketch > Plugins > Manage Plugins**.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Prototype (Optional)**\n- **Create Links**: Use the **Prototype** tab to connect artboards and create interactive flows.\n- **Preview**: Test your prototype with **Preview** mode (Cmd + P) or share it with others.\n\n---\n\n### **8. Export Your Design**\n- **Export Assets**: Select layers or artboards, then click **Make Exportable** to export in formats like PNG, SVG, or PDF.\n- **Export for Developers**: Use **Export** options to generate assets for developers.\n\n---\n\n### **Tips for Efficient Design**\n- Use **Keyboard Shortcuts** to speed up your workflow.\n- Leverage **Symbols** and **Shared Styles** for consistency.\n- Save reusable elements in **Libraries** for future projects.\n- Keep your file organized with clear naming conventions.\n\n---\n\n### **Resources**\n- **Sketch Documentation**: [https://www.sketch.com/docs/](https://www.sketch.com/docs/)\n- **Community Tutorials**: Explore platforms like YouTube or Medium for advanced tips and tricks.\n\nLet me know if you'd like help with specific features or workflows!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
